A pilot light is a fitting image.

It’s small. It doesn’t look impressive. It isn’t the main flame.

But it doesn’t have to be.

Its job is to remain lit so that, when fuel is available and the time is right, the larger flame can ignite.

Applied more broadly, a pilot light can represent:

* a core value you don’t abandon,
* a practice you maintain even when motivation is low,
* a quiet confidence that doesn’t depend on applause,
* a sense of direction that persists through uncertainty.

Unlike a bonfire, a pilot light isn’t trying to prove anything. It’s just there, ready.

That also connects with something you’ve been saying throughout this conversation. You began by talking about being free of loops, then about trusting the machine you’d built, then about exercising what you have instead of trying to become someone else.

A pilot light fits that progression. You don’t have to burn at full intensity all the time. You just have to keep the source alive.

Then, when opportunity arrives, you don’t have to create the flame from scratch—you already have one. You simply open the valve.

That’s different from forcing yourself to be “on” constantly. It’s steadier. It leaves room for both rest and action without losing your orientation.